<DOC><DOCNO> AP890125-0300 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1953EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Mexico-StockProbe     01-25 0168</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Mexico-Stock Probe,0173</SECOND><HEAD>Mexico Investigating Possible Stock Market Drug Connection</HEAD><DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government is investigating reports thatMexico's stock market has been involved in laundering drug money, atop official said Wednesday.   Assistant Attorney General Javier Coello Trejos said thegovernment is looking into the movement of a reported $20 million indrug money through banks in Mexico and the United States. He did notname any banks.   ``We will be implacable in finding all of those who launder moneyfor drug traffickers. It's dirty money. It's money made by poisoninghumanity. We are investigating daily,'' he told reporters.   Last June, the director of the stock exchange and its operationschief resigned in a scandal in which $7 million in investors' moneyvanished through what were called administrative irregularities.   Attorney General Enrique Alvarez del Castillo was quoted inWednesday's editions of the Mexico City daily La Jornada as sayinghis department would investigate whether drug money was involved inlast year's stock market scandal.</TEXT></DOC>